GUEST SPEAKER: Good morning.

00:00:23.830 --> 00:00:25.480
Today we're going to
start with a demo,

00:00:25.480 --> 00:00:28.120
and we're going to
show experimentally

00:00:28.120 --> 00:00:29.710
some of the principles
we've learned

00:00:29.710 --> 00:00:32.439
about 4F systems in
the past classes,

00:00:32.439 --> 00:00:36.820
and actually we're going to see
a comparison of an incoherent

00:00:36.820 --> 00:00:42.670
versus a coherent 4F system
when imaging resolution target.

00:00:42.670 --> 00:00:45.470
So but since now we have
all the tools to understand,

00:00:45.470 --> 00:00:48.900
finally, the set up here,
let me just describe it.

00:00:48.900 --> 00:00:50.650
I've been showing some
of these components

00:00:50.650 --> 00:00:53.680
over and over the
past demos, but I

00:00:53.680 --> 00:00:56.020
guess now we can
understand it, so

00:00:56.020 --> 00:00:58.930
let me try to focus the camera.

00:00:58.930 --> 00:01:05.600
So let me start with
this is a green laser.

00:01:05.600 --> 00:01:07.550
So the first component
that we have here

00:01:07.550 --> 00:01:10.910
is [? anti ?] filter
that its job--

00:01:10.910 --> 00:01:14.910
thank you-- so this
component, its job

00:01:14.910 --> 00:01:17.130
is to control the
intensity of light

00:01:17.130 --> 00:01:19.650
so we can attenuate it in
this case for experiment.

00:01:19.650 --> 00:01:22.410
This is an interesting component
called a spatial filter

00:01:22.410 --> 00:01:26.130
that is composed of a microscope
objective and a pinhole,

00:01:26.130 --> 00:01:30.240
and now that we know what
Fourier transforms are,

00:01:30.240 --> 00:01:31.890
the microscope
objective is essentially

00:01:31.890 --> 00:01:34.710
taking the Fourier transform
of the laser beam, which

00:01:34.710 --> 00:01:37.830
ideally is a plane wave, so
it should be a delta function.

00:01:37.830 --> 00:01:40.095
However, since this plane
wave is not perfect,

00:01:40.095 --> 00:01:42.420
it has high frequency noise.

00:01:42.420 --> 00:01:44.070
So then the pinhole,
what it does

00:01:44.070 --> 00:01:46.380
is it does a low-pass
spatial filtering.

00:01:46.380 --> 00:01:49.680
So it basically removes all
these high frequency signal,

00:01:49.680 --> 00:01:52.720
and after these we have a nice
spherical wave coming out.

00:01:52.720 --> 00:01:55.380
This component here
is an iris, control

00:01:55.380 --> 00:01:57.510
the diameter of
this spherical wave,

00:01:57.510 --> 00:02:00.720
and this element here
is my collimating lens

00:02:00.720 --> 00:02:03.720
that will transform this
spherical wave into a plane

00:02:03.720 --> 00:02:04.500
wave.

00:02:04.500 --> 00:02:07.030
In this case, this is
just a beam splitter

00:02:07.030 --> 00:02:09.930
that will allow me to
couple from this side, where

00:02:09.930 --> 00:02:12.060
I have a white light source.

00:02:12.060 --> 00:02:16.000
In this white light source,
we have a green filter,

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:18.870
so then we only have
green light coming out.

00:02:18.870 --> 00:02:20.850
We have an iris again
to control the diameter.

00:02:20.850 --> 00:02:23.190
Right now I'm blocking
it, so it is a beam block.

00:02:23.190 --> 00:02:24.960
And these are collimating lens.

00:02:24.960 --> 00:02:27.480
So here it should be
the planar equivalent

00:02:27.480 --> 00:02:28.650
of the incoherent side.

00:02:28.650 --> 00:02:31.350
This is the planar equivalent
of the coherent side.

00:02:31.350 --> 00:02:36.930
This mirror here bends the
light 90 degrees to send it

00:02:36.930 --> 00:02:39.330
to the side from here.

00:02:39.330 --> 00:02:41.340
This is the one line
of the incoherent line,

00:02:41.340 --> 00:02:43.680
and then should go
into the common path

00:02:43.680 --> 00:02:46.500
of the coherent line.

00:02:46.500 --> 00:02:50.080
Then they basically
bend again 90 degrees,

00:02:50.080 --> 00:02:52.660
and this is the
4F system section.

00:02:52.660 --> 00:02:55.710
So here we have first an
element, which is the object

00:02:55.710 --> 00:02:57.390
that we want to image.

00:02:57.390 --> 00:02:59.640
The object is called
the resolution target,

00:02:59.640 --> 00:03:03.150
and it's a clear substrate,
so a piece of glass

00:03:03.150 --> 00:03:07.510
that has patterned chrome lines
of smaller and smaller sizes

00:03:07.510 --> 00:03:09.090
that we're going to see.

00:03:09.090 --> 00:03:12.000
Then we have our first
lens of the 4F system.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:14.620
This is a non-magnifying
4F system,

00:03:14.620 --> 00:03:17.950
so these two lenses are
exactly the same focal length.

00:03:17.950 --> 00:03:19.170
So first lens.

00:03:19.170 --> 00:03:22.020
Then this is an aperture
in the Fourier plane

00:03:22.020 --> 00:03:25.260
because we're going to start
with low-pass filtering.

00:03:25.260 --> 00:03:28.200
The second lens, and
then we're imaging this

00:03:28.200 --> 00:03:32.010
into our detector, which
uses CCD seamless array.

00:03:37.260 --> 00:03:39.170
So now we're going to
switch to the camera

00:03:39.170 --> 00:03:40.790
and start with a coherent case.

00:04:02.880 --> 00:04:07.440
So the first case, it's like
what we've seen in class.

00:04:07.440 --> 00:04:11.980
We're going to illuminate this
object with an inline plane

00:04:11.980 --> 00:04:12.480
wave.

00:04:16.430 --> 00:04:18.740
OK, let me just zoom
in a little bit.

00:04:21.790 --> 00:04:23.210
So this is the
resolution target,

00:04:23.210 --> 00:04:25.130
and it's in imaging
condition, right?

00:04:25.130 --> 00:04:28.010
So the object is in the front
focal plane of the first lens,

00:04:28.010 --> 00:04:31.580
and the detector is in the back
focal plane of the second lens.

00:04:31.580 --> 00:04:34.940
So what you can see
here is we are actually

00:04:34.940 --> 00:04:38.400
imaging all the way to
groups two and three.

00:04:38.400 --> 00:04:40.900
This resolution target
has lines even larger,

00:04:40.900 --> 00:04:43.400
which are one and two
that we don't see here.

00:04:43.400 --> 00:04:46.650
And the first thing we
see is the following.

00:04:46.650 --> 00:04:49.310
We see some fringes,
which are produced

00:04:49.310 --> 00:04:51.860
by the interference
from the glass,

00:04:51.860 --> 00:04:54.500
so it's basically the reflection
of the plane waves interfering

00:04:54.500 --> 00:04:56.340
with each other.

00:04:56.340 --> 00:05:01.760
So this is very typical
in coherent imaging.

00:05:01.760 --> 00:05:06.860
We see other rings that are
produced by dust particles

00:05:06.860 --> 00:05:08.490
maybe along the way.

00:05:08.490 --> 00:05:11.360
So all these fringes right now
look destructive to the image,

00:05:11.360 --> 00:05:13.770
and perhaps they are for
certain applications.

00:05:13.770 --> 00:05:17.120
However, for those of you
doing digital holography,

00:05:17.120 --> 00:05:20.240
you notice that these fringes
contain a lot of information

00:05:20.240 --> 00:05:23.030
that is encoded about the
amplitude and the phase

00:05:23.030 --> 00:05:25.760
of the signal that
we can exploit.

00:05:25.760 --> 00:05:27.870
So just for
comparison, I'm going

00:05:27.870 --> 00:05:34.030
to zoom in and see what is the
maximum that we can see here.

00:05:34.030 --> 00:05:38.100
So you can see that we can have
a resolution now that we know

00:05:38.100 --> 00:05:40.770
what the optimal resolution.

00:05:40.770 --> 00:05:42.690
With good accuracy
we see maybe down

00:05:42.690 --> 00:05:46.330
to this side of the
group number five.

00:05:46.330 --> 00:05:48.550
All right, so in the
homework we learned

00:05:48.550 --> 00:05:53.673
about the low-pass
filtering in Fourier domain.

00:05:53.673 --> 00:05:55.090
So just to remind
you, essentially

00:05:55.090 --> 00:05:58.120
what we're going to do
is that the first lens

00:05:58.120 --> 00:05:59.980
is taking the Fourier
transform, and it

00:05:59.980 --> 00:06:02.110
happens in the Fourier plane.

00:06:02.110 --> 00:06:05.260
So then in that plane
we put an aperture,

00:06:05.260 --> 00:06:07.630
centered, and then
what we do is we're

00:06:07.630 --> 00:06:11.080
going to start reducing the
diameter of the aperture

00:06:11.080 --> 00:06:14.930
to try to low-pass filter
the signal more and more.

00:06:14.930 --> 00:06:17.500
So what do we
expect to see here?

00:06:17.500 --> 00:06:19.720
Well, you did it
in the p-set, so we

00:06:19.720 --> 00:06:22.480
expect to see some blurring,
progressive blurring.

00:06:22.480 --> 00:06:24.160
So I'm going to do
it, and hopefully you

00:06:24.160 --> 00:06:25.220
can see it from there.

00:06:25.220 --> 00:06:31.963
So right now it's all open,
and I'm going to blur it.

00:06:31.963 --> 00:06:33.130
So I'm going to do it again.

00:06:33.130 --> 00:06:36.150
This is clear.

00:06:36.150 --> 00:06:36.650
Blurry.

00:06:40.470 --> 00:06:43.590
So I'm controlling
with this iris.

00:06:43.590 --> 00:06:47.760
And you can see how the signal
that contains the higher

00:06:47.760 --> 00:06:51.360
spatial frequency in
this area goes first,

00:06:51.360 --> 00:06:55.200
then this one and this one.

00:06:55.200 --> 00:06:56.850
But all of them now--

00:06:56.850 --> 00:07:03.230
in this blurry condition,
if I try to zoom back again,

00:07:03.230 --> 00:07:06.220
now we see how the
signal is really blurry.

00:07:06.220 --> 00:07:09.430
If I open the aperture,
it becomes clear again.

00:07:12.268 --> 00:07:14.560
So now let's do the comparison
of the exact same thing.

00:07:14.560 --> 00:07:17.800
What would you think it would
happen if I switch illumination

00:07:17.800 --> 00:07:21.300
now to incoherent light?

00:07:21.300 --> 00:07:24.790
So I'm going to block the
coherent light here, and then

00:07:24.790 --> 00:07:28.270
the first thing that we
notice is that we don't have

00:07:28.270 --> 00:07:30.040
those fringes anymore, right?

00:07:30.040 --> 00:07:33.400
So it looks like a
very clean image.

00:07:35.888 --> 00:07:37.680
So again, in this case,
you can think about

00:07:37.680 --> 00:07:40.500
that for microscopy,
this is very nice.

00:07:40.500 --> 00:07:43.350
However, from the digital
holographic point of view,

00:07:43.350 --> 00:07:45.330
we don't have that
extra information

00:07:45.330 --> 00:07:49.620
that we can use in
encoding of the signal.

00:07:49.620 --> 00:07:52.890
Now let me zoom in to compare
the resolution in this case.

00:07:58.230 --> 00:08:01.350
So you can see it's
hard to tell if we don't

00:08:01.350 --> 00:08:06.900
do a quantitative study to see
exactly what is the smallest

00:08:06.900 --> 00:08:08.500
line that we can
see in each case,

00:08:08.500 --> 00:08:10.230
but we can see the
comparison again

00:08:10.230 --> 00:08:14.400
versus the resolution in the
coherent and incoherent cases.

00:08:14.400 --> 00:08:17.800
And now let's do the
low-pass filtering.

00:08:17.800 --> 00:08:20.140
So again, this aperture
right now is fully open,

00:08:20.140 --> 00:08:21.390
and then I started closing it.

00:08:26.040 --> 00:08:28.280
And I'm closing and
closing and closing it.

00:08:31.130 --> 00:08:33.630
Open again.

00:08:33.630 --> 00:08:35.470
Close it.

00:08:35.470 --> 00:08:37.820
So we see two things.

00:08:37.820 --> 00:08:40.809
Remember that the incoherent
system is basically regulated

00:08:40.809 --> 00:08:44.685
by the OTF, as opposed to the
ATF in the coherent system.

00:08:44.685 --> 00:08:46.060
So now that you
can think of it--

00:08:46.060 --> 00:08:50.230
the easy terms is it's a
[? combo ?] because the OTF is

00:08:50.230 --> 00:08:55.510
a normalized cross
correlation of the ATF, which

00:08:55.510 --> 00:08:58.450
means that when I
close this aperture,

00:08:58.450 --> 00:09:02.200
you can see how the
signal becomes weaker

00:09:02.200 --> 00:09:05.950
and weaker because essentially
I'm restricting the DC

00:09:05.950 --> 00:09:09.250
component that happens to
be in all the signal there,

00:09:09.250 --> 00:09:10.600
but also gets blurry.

00:09:10.600 --> 00:09:14.370
It's hard to see, but
it's getting blurry.

00:09:14.370 --> 00:09:16.780
It is getting blurry
at a different rate

00:09:16.780 --> 00:09:17.710
as the other system.

00:09:23.560 --> 00:09:25.890
So now let's go to
high-pass filter,

00:09:25.890 --> 00:09:30.490
and I'm going to switch
back to the coherent case.

00:09:30.490 --> 00:09:31.900
So this is the coherent case.

00:09:31.900 --> 00:09:33.275
So right now what
I'm going to do

00:09:33.275 --> 00:09:36.640
is that I'm going to remove the
aperture in the Fourier plane,

00:09:36.640 --> 00:09:41.880
and I just did a very improvised
high-pass filter, which

00:09:41.880 --> 00:09:45.150
basically is a microscope slide
that has a little piece of tape

00:09:45.150 --> 00:09:49.020
in the center just to block the
basic component, or kind of,

00:09:49.020 --> 00:09:49.980
but anyways, it works.

00:09:59.400 --> 00:10:03.690
Somewhere around here--
let me crank up the light.

00:10:09.080 --> 00:10:12.770
And we can see how basically
we remove the DC term.

00:10:17.810 --> 00:10:20.090
And you see the high-pass
filtering effect,

00:10:20.090 --> 00:10:23.480
which is essentially
accentuating

00:10:23.480 --> 00:10:24.740
all the edges of the signal.

00:10:32.110 --> 00:10:34.070
Now I'm going to put
the incoherent case

00:10:34.070 --> 00:10:39.697
and the coherent superimposed
just to show edge detection.

00:10:39.697 --> 00:10:40.780
So this is a normal thing.

00:10:40.780 --> 00:10:42.442
We can accentuate the edges.

00:10:42.442 --> 00:10:43.900
So what is interesting
also here is

00:10:43.900 --> 00:10:46.990
that if you move the
filter in different places,

00:10:46.990 --> 00:10:50.890
you can, say, just
accentuate the edges

00:10:50.890 --> 00:10:54.520
in the horizontal direction or
in the vertical direction, et

00:10:54.520 --> 00:10:55.270
cetera, et cetera.

00:10:58.910 --> 00:11:01.270
We see that the
incoherent case, we

00:11:01.270 --> 00:11:04.510
don't see the same effect,
which is as expected.

00:11:04.510 --> 00:11:06.850
Again, it's a normalized
cross correlation.

00:11:06.850 --> 00:11:10.780
But with a coherent case, we
do see these drastic change.

