00:14:46.560 --> 00:14:53.290
So the way we analyze the
system, of course, is we'll

00:14:53.290 --> 00:14:57.070
basically have to propagate
using Fresnel diffraction

00:14:57.070 --> 00:15:00.370
to propagate the field from
one element to the next

00:15:00.370 --> 00:15:02.510
until we reach the
end of the system.

00:15:02.510 --> 00:15:06.483
So for example, at the input
we have the input field.

00:15:06.483 --> 00:15:07.900
I will write it
in one [INAUDIBLE]

00:15:07.900 --> 00:15:10.070
so we don't write too much.

00:15:10.070 --> 00:15:12.190
The input field is
simply the product

00:15:12.190 --> 00:15:22.920
of the illumination field times
the complex transmittivity

00:15:22.920 --> 00:15:24.750
of the input transparency.

00:15:24.750 --> 00:15:30.380
I will do everything
for a spatially coherent

00:15:30.380 --> 00:15:34.600
illumination, and we know now
that if the illumination is

00:15:34.600 --> 00:15:37.805
spatially incoherent,
if we have already

00:15:37.805 --> 00:15:39.680
solved the coherent
case, we're in good shape

00:15:39.680 --> 00:15:42.735
because we can simply take the
modular square of the point

00:15:42.735 --> 00:15:44.360
spread function and
the autocorrelation

00:15:44.360 --> 00:15:48.240
of the coherent amplitude
transfer function,

00:15:48.240 --> 00:15:50.520
and then we can compute the
correspondent quantities

00:15:50.520 --> 00:15:51.710
for the incoherent case.

00:15:51.710 --> 00:15:55.350
So the coherent is the one
that we'll always start with.

00:15:55.350 --> 00:15:58.540
OK, so doing that now, we
can calculate, for example,

00:15:58.540 --> 00:16:02.280
the field immediately
to the left of the lens.

00:16:09.310 --> 00:16:14.650
So let's call it g
sub L minus for left,

00:16:14.650 --> 00:16:21.660
and I think I still use x
double prime as my coordinate.

00:16:21.660 --> 00:16:25.940
So this is now a Fresnel
propagated version

00:16:25.940 --> 00:16:30.560
of the input field, so we'll
write out the big, bad Fresnel

00:16:30.560 --> 00:16:31.680
integral.

00:16:31.680 --> 00:16:36.320
e the i 2 pi z1 over
lambda i lambda z1.

00:16:36.320 --> 00:16:38.080
So this is the
[? prequel, ?] and then we

00:16:38.080 --> 00:16:40.400
write our big
integral here, g sub

00:16:40.400 --> 00:16:43.340
in of x, and then the quadratic.

00:16:52.810 --> 00:16:57.250
And of course, two things
happen at the lens plane.

00:16:57.250 --> 00:16:58.840
First of all is the lens itself.

00:16:58.840 --> 00:17:01.900
That will impose an additional
quadratic phase delay

00:17:01.900 --> 00:17:03.970
upon the signal, but
now it's a little bit

00:17:03.970 --> 00:17:06.339
different than the
geometrical optics case.

00:17:06.339 --> 00:17:08.440
I forgot to mention
earlier that I

00:17:08.440 --> 00:17:14.480
have added a thin transparency
in front of the lens.

00:17:14.480 --> 00:17:16.450
So this is again a pupil mask.

00:17:16.450 --> 00:17:18.400
As we will see in
a moment, it does

00:17:18.400 --> 00:17:21.339
pretty much the same
job as the pupil mask

00:17:21.339 --> 00:17:25.640
did at the Fourier plane of the
4F system, but in this case,

00:17:25.640 --> 00:17:30.067
we actually put it sort of
in contact with the lens.

00:17:30.067 --> 00:17:31.150
In fact, we don't have to.

00:17:31.150 --> 00:17:33.340
We can put the mask
anywhere we like,

00:17:33.340 --> 00:17:36.690
but anyway, it makes the math
a bit simpler in this case.

00:17:36.690 --> 00:17:39.580
And in most implementations,
for practical reasons,

00:17:39.580 --> 00:17:41.950
they also do it this way
because it is much better

00:17:41.950 --> 00:17:44.410
to have everything
stacked together,

00:17:44.410 --> 00:17:46.450
as opposed to having
different elements

00:17:46.450 --> 00:17:49.070
sort of floating around
in an optical system.

00:17:49.070 --> 00:17:53.320
OK, so this means then that
the field to the right hand

00:17:53.320 --> 00:17:57.310
side of the lens, so the
plus now means to the right,

00:17:57.310 --> 00:17:59.500
still x double
prime coordinates,

00:17:59.500 --> 00:18:03.040
is going to equal to
the field that was

00:18:03.040 --> 00:18:07.480
on the left multiplied by 2.

00:18:07.480 --> 00:18:08.680
Two functions now.

00:18:08.680 --> 00:18:11.960
One is the thin
transparency itself,

00:18:11.960 --> 00:18:14.800
which I denote
there as g sub pm.

00:18:14.800 --> 00:18:16.720
pm, of course, stands
for pupil mask,

00:18:16.720 --> 00:18:20.570
like in the previous cases.

00:18:20.570 --> 00:18:25.730
And then times another
complex quadratic

00:18:25.730 --> 00:18:28.860
exponential that corresponds
to the lens itself.

00:18:28.860 --> 00:18:31.880
So this would be e
to the minus i pi x

00:18:31.880 --> 00:18:36.300
double prime square
upon lambda f,

00:18:36.300 --> 00:18:40.610
where f is the focal
length of the lens.

00:18:40.610 --> 00:18:43.565
And finally, the
field at the output.

00:18:48.720 --> 00:18:51.410
Now the output
coordinate is x prime.

00:18:51.410 --> 00:18:55.190
It's going to equal
another Fresnel propagation

00:18:55.190 --> 00:18:58.250
from the pupil mask
to the output plain,

00:18:58.250 --> 00:19:01.820
so I have to write another
propagation term here.

00:19:01.820 --> 00:19:03.470
This would be z2 this time.

00:19:06.430 --> 00:19:12.980
And what I will put now is gL
plus because this is the field

00:19:12.980 --> 00:19:17.340
to the right of the right of
the composite lens and the pupil

00:19:17.340 --> 00:19:20.990
mask, so that would be
x double prime and then

00:19:20.990 --> 00:19:23.015
another quadratic exponential.

00:19:35.400 --> 00:19:42.978
OK, so this is it, and when
you plug in all this math--

00:19:42.978 --> 00:19:44.520
this is something
we've done already,

00:19:44.520 --> 00:19:47.380
so I will not do it
in the class again,

00:19:47.380 --> 00:19:49.000
but there is a supplement.

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:51.400
There is a scan of
my handwritten notes

00:19:51.400 --> 00:19:54.310
in the website where you will
see a little bit more detail

00:19:54.310 --> 00:19:56.257
on how I did the
derivation here,

00:19:56.257 --> 00:19:58.090
but I will skip some
of the immediate steps,

00:19:58.090 --> 00:20:00.110
and I will show the result here.

00:20:00.110 --> 00:20:02.590
So the way you handle this
kind of-- as you imagine,

00:20:02.590 --> 00:20:04.360
when you combine all
of these integrals,

00:20:04.360 --> 00:20:08.700
you will get a sort of
integral that involves all

00:20:08.700 --> 00:20:13.990
of these functions, g sub
in, g sub pm and so on,

00:20:13.990 --> 00:20:17.060
but also you will have a bunch
of quadratic exponentials.

00:20:17.060 --> 00:20:19.480
So what you do is you
expand the exponents

00:20:19.480 --> 00:20:26.620
of these exponentials,
and you rearrange terms,

00:20:26.620 --> 00:20:29.120
and you write it out this way.

00:20:29.120 --> 00:20:30.670
So these are the
output coordinates.

00:20:30.670 --> 00:20:32.720
They don't participate
in the integration,

00:20:32.720 --> 00:20:35.440
so we can knock them
out of the integral.

00:20:35.440 --> 00:20:38.020
And then of course, we cannot
do much about this thing

00:20:38.020 --> 00:20:42.460
because, well, we don't know
what these functions are yet,

00:20:42.460 --> 00:20:45.940
but we can certainly try
to see what we can do with

00:20:45.940 --> 00:20:47.150
the remainder.

00:20:47.150 --> 00:20:52.600
So what is sort of glaring
here is that in the exponent,

00:20:52.600 --> 00:20:56.650
you have quadratic terms, and
you also have linear terms.

00:20:56.650 --> 00:20:58.630
The linear terms, we
know from experience

00:20:58.630 --> 00:21:01.030
that they lead into Fourier
transform, so they're nice.

00:21:01.030 --> 00:21:02.560
We'll know what to do with them.

00:21:02.560 --> 00:21:04.420
The quadratic
terms, they usually

00:21:04.420 --> 00:21:08.960
correspond to nasty things like
the focus, but in this case,

00:21:08.960 --> 00:21:11.380
you can see that the
quadratic term is multiplied

00:21:11.380 --> 00:21:13.990
by a coefficient
here, which allows

00:21:13.990 --> 00:21:16.030
us to knock it out if
we select the distance

00:21:16.030 --> 00:21:20.740
as z1 and z2 judiciously,
and of course that

00:21:20.740 --> 00:21:23.290
is the result of the lens law.

00:21:23.290 --> 00:21:25.330
This is the same
equation that we

00:21:25.330 --> 00:21:27.070
derived using
geometrical optics,

00:21:27.070 --> 00:21:29.180
and we'll call it the
imaging condition.

00:21:29.180 --> 00:21:31.600
So you can see here that when
you satisfied this imaging

00:21:31.600 --> 00:21:35.620
condition, then you essentially
knock out the focus term

00:21:35.620 --> 00:21:37.450
from the diffraction integral.

00:21:37.450 --> 00:21:40.060
So that is gratifying
because we actually

00:21:40.060 --> 00:21:43.390
derived a result from
geometrical optics,

00:21:43.390 --> 00:21:46.510
but this time it is perhaps
more rigorous because it

00:21:46.510 --> 00:21:48.328
is based on electromagnetics.

00:21:51.365 --> 00:21:52.240
What is the rest now?

00:21:52.240 --> 00:21:54.880
Well, we'll deal with
the rest in a moment,

00:21:54.880 --> 00:21:59.710
but you see that there's another
quadratic here that we cannot

00:21:59.710 --> 00:22:05.530
quite so easily get rid of,
and this extra quadratic that

00:22:05.530 --> 00:22:10.750
popped up there is interesting
because it is not predicted

00:22:10.750 --> 00:22:11.900
by geometrical optics.

00:22:11.900 --> 00:22:13.988
So this is something that--

00:22:13.988 --> 00:22:16.030
well, it will happen only
with spatially coherent

00:22:16.030 --> 00:22:21.750
illumination, and geometrical
optics cannot predict it

00:22:21.750 --> 00:22:24.560
and actually cannot
deal with it.

00:22:24.560 --> 00:22:26.830
And in fact, not so
long ago, about the time

00:22:26.830 --> 00:22:29.793
I was born in the
early '70s, this

00:22:29.793 --> 00:22:31.960
was a topic of research,
what to do about this term.

00:22:31.960 --> 00:22:36.550
In fact, Professor Goodman,
who wrote your textbook, one

00:22:36.550 --> 00:22:41.680
of his early results
as a young scientist,

00:22:41.680 --> 00:22:45.160
he wrote the famous
paper about this term,

00:22:45.160 --> 00:22:46.120
what this term means.

00:22:46.120 --> 00:22:46.828
And he wrote it--

00:22:46.828 --> 00:22:50.140
I believe he wrote it in 1971,
exactly the year I was born.

00:22:50.140 --> 00:22:52.750
I'm not that old, so I
guess that you can still

00:22:52.750 --> 00:22:57.300
call it a relatively
recent development.

00:22:57.300 --> 00:22:59.980
So again, we're talking
about this term over here,

00:22:59.980 --> 00:23:02.290
what to do about this one.

00:23:02.290 --> 00:23:08.650
And then of course, there's
an entire section in Goodman

00:23:08.650 --> 00:23:11.050
that talks about this
term, and I would encourage

00:23:11.050 --> 00:23:12.480
you to read the section.

00:23:12.480 --> 00:23:16.120
I will show a summary here.

00:23:16.120 --> 00:23:18.705
Something got messed up that
with my animations here.

00:23:18.705 --> 00:23:20.580
This was not supposed
to be here, but anyway.

00:23:24.240 --> 00:23:27.750
So Goodman actually
goes over three methods

00:23:27.750 --> 00:23:31.440
that you can use to eliminate
this unwanted quadratic.

00:23:31.440 --> 00:23:36.180
One of them is you lay out the
input transparency as a sphere,

00:23:36.180 --> 00:23:37.680
or in a spherical
surface, instead

00:23:37.680 --> 00:23:39.210
of the typical planar surface.

00:23:39.210 --> 00:23:40.710
That may sound a
little bit strange,

00:23:40.710 --> 00:23:43.992
and it's probably very difficult
to implement in practice,

00:23:43.992 --> 00:23:45.450
but conceptually
you can see what's

00:23:45.450 --> 00:23:49.440
going on because now these
points in the transparency

00:23:49.440 --> 00:23:51.930
start with an
original phase delay,

00:23:51.930 --> 00:23:53.700
you can work out the
curvature right here.

00:23:53.700 --> 00:23:55.075
In fact, the
curvature would have

00:23:55.075 --> 00:23:57.480
to be exactly z1, the
areas of curvature,

00:23:57.480 --> 00:23:59.760
so that it cancels this
unwanted quadratic.

00:23:59.760 --> 00:24:01.770
So that's one way.

00:24:01.770 --> 00:24:04.590
The second way is
to actually stick

00:24:04.590 --> 00:24:07.830
a lens in front of
the transparency.

00:24:07.830 --> 00:24:12.390
This is actually very often done
in geometrical optics as well.

00:24:12.390 --> 00:24:13.890
This is called the
condenser lens.

00:24:13.890 --> 00:24:17.130
So for example, we
don't have this anymore,

00:24:17.130 --> 00:24:19.710
but actually, we do have
one in the classroom.

00:24:19.710 --> 00:24:24.330
We used to use these projectors.

00:24:24.330 --> 00:24:28.650
Basically, if you look at the
top surface of this projector--

00:24:28.650 --> 00:24:30.450
I don't know if I can
take it out here--

00:24:30.450 --> 00:24:32.790
but if you look at it,
it's actually a lens.

00:24:32.790 --> 00:24:34.570
After class, come over and look.

00:24:34.570 --> 00:24:39.240
There is grooves on
it, and basically,

00:24:39.240 --> 00:24:43.590
sort of the grooves implement
equivalent of a lens surface.

00:24:47.090 --> 00:24:56.730
If you do the operation modulo
2 pi on the surface of the lens,

00:24:56.730 --> 00:25:01.350
instead of having this
surface that we typically

00:25:01.350 --> 00:25:03.867
think of as a lens, if you
do a modulo 2 pi operation,

00:25:03.867 --> 00:25:05.700
you will get something
like this, of course.

00:25:14.370 --> 00:25:18.800
OK, so that's a way
to make a thin lens.

00:25:18.800 --> 00:25:21.050
That is called a condenser.

00:25:21.050 --> 00:25:22.520
The reason we put
it in a projector

00:25:22.520 --> 00:25:24.530
is not to eliminate
this quadratic factor,

00:25:24.530 --> 00:25:29.750
it is simply because it makes
the illumination uniform.

00:25:29.750 --> 00:25:32.143
So when you project
the slide on--

00:25:32.143 --> 00:25:33.560
I don't know if
you guys are maybe

00:25:33.560 --> 00:25:35.480
too young to have
ever seen anything

00:25:35.480 --> 00:25:38.002
like this in operation, but
the next time if I remember,

00:25:38.002 --> 00:25:39.710
I'll bring an old
fashioned transparency,

00:25:39.710 --> 00:25:42.260
and I will show you
how people of my age

00:25:42.260 --> 00:25:43.820
used to give talks
at conferences

00:25:43.820 --> 00:25:47.040
when we didn't have PowerPoint.

00:25:47.040 --> 00:25:51.350
But anyway, this is done
actually very commonly,

00:25:51.350 --> 00:25:53.300
to stick a lens in front of--

00:25:53.300 --> 00:25:55.707
just attached to a thin object.

00:25:55.707 --> 00:25:57.540
But there are some cases
you cannot do that.

00:25:57.540 --> 00:25:58.957
For example, in
the microscope, it

00:25:58.957 --> 00:26:00.890
is very difficult
to imagine sticking

00:26:00.890 --> 00:26:04.640
a lens behind the glass slide.

00:26:04.640 --> 00:26:06.890
So in some cases,
this is applicable,

00:26:06.890 --> 00:26:07.960
and in some it is not.

00:26:07.960 --> 00:26:11.720
Anyway, a big application
of this type of lens

00:26:11.720 --> 00:26:14.120
is of course in
overhead projectors.

00:26:14.120 --> 00:26:15.830
Does anybody know
another application

00:26:15.830 --> 00:26:17.630
where people use
this kind of lenses,

00:26:17.630 --> 00:26:21.527
or what might motivate you
to make this kind of lens?

00:26:21.527 --> 00:26:22.110
Can you think?

00:26:28.450 --> 00:26:30.170
These lenses are commonly used--

00:26:30.170 --> 00:26:30.980
actually, you know?

00:26:33.887 --> 00:26:35.470
AUDIENCE: Do they
sometimes stick them

00:26:35.470 --> 00:26:38.413
on the backs of vans or
cars to make it wide angle?

00:26:38.413 --> 00:26:40.080
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
That's right, yeah.

00:26:40.080 --> 00:26:42.160
That's another application.

00:26:42.160 --> 00:26:46.163
Exactly, to improve the
rear view of the driver.

00:26:46.163 --> 00:26:47.080
And that's a good one.

00:26:47.080 --> 00:26:49.330
I wasn't thinking of that.

00:26:49.330 --> 00:26:54.970
Yet another one is in very
high power illuminators,

00:26:54.970 --> 00:26:59.350
which are most commonly used in
photography in shooting movies

00:26:59.350 --> 00:27:06.460
because the glass, as you know,
is not a very good conductor,

00:27:06.460 --> 00:27:10.610
so it would hit up very
badly if you illuminate

00:27:10.610 --> 00:27:13.590
with very high power.

00:27:13.590 --> 00:27:15.350
They're called,
actually, babies,

00:27:15.350 --> 00:27:17.830
these really big
light bulbs that they

00:27:17.830 --> 00:27:19.780
use when they shoot movies.

00:27:19.780 --> 00:27:21.490
So they actually use these.

00:27:21.490 --> 00:27:24.590
It is called a Fresnel
lens, the same Fresnel

00:27:24.590 --> 00:27:28.550
lens in Fresnel propagation.

00:27:28.550 --> 00:27:34.280
So they use the Fresnel lenses
in these so-called babies.

00:27:34.280 --> 00:27:36.170
All right.

00:27:36.170 --> 00:27:39.200
And lighthouses also, yeah.

00:27:39.200 --> 00:27:42.890
So again, every time that
you have a really huge light

00:27:42.890 --> 00:27:43.390
source.

00:27:43.390 --> 00:27:45.598
Of course, it's a matter of
practicality also, right?

00:27:45.598 --> 00:27:48.680
If you have a major
lens, as you can imagine,

00:27:48.680 --> 00:27:51.470
if the diameter is big,
then also this size

00:27:51.470 --> 00:27:52.750
would also be very big, right?

00:27:52.750 --> 00:27:54.170
So in a lighthouse,
you might have

00:27:54.170 --> 00:27:57.980
a lens that is maybe 1
or 2 meters in diameter,

00:27:57.980 --> 00:28:00.947
then it would have to bulge
over another half meter or so.

00:28:00.947 --> 00:28:02.030
That's not very practical.

00:28:02.030 --> 00:28:04.252
It is heavy, fragile,
blah blah blah.

00:28:04.252 --> 00:28:06.710
So they make the Fresnel lenses
to get around this problem.

00:28:09.805 --> 00:28:11.420
A good thing to
remember about those

00:28:11.420 --> 00:28:15.330
is that they generally give
very poor image quality.

00:28:15.330 --> 00:28:18.850
So if you try to use
this as an imaging lens,

00:28:18.850 --> 00:28:23.180
you typically get a very bad
blur and a very bad image

00:28:23.180 --> 00:28:27.530
quality, but obviously in the
lighthouse you don't care.

00:28:27.530 --> 00:28:29.540
In an illuminator,
you don't care.

00:28:29.540 --> 00:28:33.470
And also the projector, it is
not used as an imaging lens.

00:28:33.470 --> 00:28:35.990
The imaging lens is a
real lens, this one.

00:28:35.990 --> 00:28:38.270
This is simply collimating
the illumination

00:28:38.270 --> 00:28:43.220
so you get a uniform
image at the image plane.

00:28:43.220 --> 00:28:45.890
So for jobs like this
one where you basically

00:28:45.890 --> 00:28:48.830
want to take a light bulb
that is highly un-uniform.

00:28:48.830 --> 00:28:51.300
It has filaments,
all kinds of crap.

00:28:51.300 --> 00:28:54.080
So this is a very
nonuniform field.

00:28:54.080 --> 00:28:57.200
This type of lens is
very good to uniformize

00:28:57.200 --> 00:28:58.940
the intensity,
and then of course

00:28:58.940 --> 00:29:01.343
if you need to image
a sharp object,

00:29:01.343 --> 00:29:02.510
then you need the real lens.

00:29:02.510 --> 00:29:05.550
You cannot get around that.

00:29:05.550 --> 00:29:09.540
OK, that's a bit
about Fresnel lenses.

00:29:09.540 --> 00:29:12.180
So that's a bit
of a detour, but I

00:29:12.180 --> 00:29:14.760
wanted to point out
some practical ways

00:29:14.760 --> 00:29:18.030
that you might be able
to do this kind of thing

00:29:18.030 --> 00:29:19.860
if you need to get
rid of the lens.

00:29:19.860 --> 00:29:23.980
And finally, what John Goodman
proved back when he was young

00:29:23.980 --> 00:29:28.710
is that there's a
condition that you can

00:29:28.710 --> 00:29:31.453
neglect this nasty quadratic.

00:29:31.453 --> 00:29:33.120
Again, we're talking
about the quadratic

00:29:33.120 --> 00:29:35.330
that you see at the
top of the slide.

00:29:35.330 --> 00:29:41.280
So it turns out if the
field of the object--

00:29:41.280 --> 00:29:43.950
when we say the field,
sometimes in geometrical optics

00:29:43.950 --> 00:29:46.000
we mean the size of this.

00:29:46.000 --> 00:29:49.950
So if the field is smaller
than about a quarter

00:29:49.950 --> 00:29:53.220
of the imaging lens,
then it turns out again

00:29:53.220 --> 00:30:01.380
that the effects of this
term are negligible,

00:30:01.380 --> 00:30:04.680
and therefore we can get rid
of it in clear conscience.

00:30:04.680 --> 00:30:07.580
So I will not go
into the details.

00:30:07.580 --> 00:30:10.140
There is discussion
in the book and also

00:30:10.140 --> 00:30:13.830
reference 303 from
the book is an article

00:30:13.830 --> 00:30:17.040
that Goodman wrote
back then, and he

00:30:17.040 --> 00:30:19.140
goes into this in a
little bit more detail.

00:30:19.140 --> 00:30:21.622
It's a pretty
interesting article.

00:30:21.622 --> 00:30:23.830
I'm going to leave a post
on the website if you like.

00:30:23.830 --> 00:30:25.520
It's pretty interesting to read.

00:30:28.370 --> 00:30:32.580
So assuming then that will get
rid of this extra quadratic--

00:30:32.580 --> 00:30:33.450
let me go back one.

00:30:39.240 --> 00:30:42.820
So we got rid of one
quadratic from the lens law,

00:30:42.820 --> 00:30:47.560
and I spent a lot of time
arguing about this quadratic,

00:30:47.560 --> 00:30:49.200
that maybe you can
get rid of that

00:30:49.200 --> 00:30:53.980
then as well, assuming you
can get rid of that as well.

00:30:53.980 --> 00:30:55.930
Well, anyway, even
if we don't get rid

00:30:55.930 --> 00:30:59.290
of that, what is left in here
is actually Fourier transform.

00:30:59.290 --> 00:31:01.060
I think I pointed
that out before.

00:31:01.060 --> 00:31:02.290
A Fourier transform-- why?

00:31:02.290 --> 00:31:04.480
Because you have
linear now, linear

00:31:04.480 --> 00:31:08.520
exponents times
some coefficient,

00:31:08.520 --> 00:31:10.580
and then here you
have the pupil mask.

00:31:10.580 --> 00:31:12.330
So again you recognize
something familiar.

00:31:12.330 --> 00:31:15.210
The same thing happened in
the case of the 4F system.

00:31:15.210 --> 00:31:17.580
We again got a
term like this one,

00:31:17.580 --> 00:31:19.690
but it was slightly different.

00:31:19.690 --> 00:31:23.660
Instead of z1 z2 in
the denominators here,

00:31:23.660 --> 00:31:26.880
it had f1 and f2, the
two focal lengths.

00:31:26.880 --> 00:31:30.210
Here we have the two distances,
but it's pretty much the same,

00:31:30.210 --> 00:31:34.680
and again the pupil mask
appeared in the kernel here.

00:31:34.680 --> 00:31:38.130
So this is a Fourier
transform, and of course we

00:31:38.130 --> 00:31:41.890
get rid of this term, and let
me jump through these animations

00:31:41.890 --> 00:31:42.390
now.

00:31:45.990 --> 00:31:50.010
OK, so if we're doing that,
then what we finally get

00:31:50.010 --> 00:31:54.480
is this expression
here, where, again, this

00:31:54.480 --> 00:31:57.690
is the Fourier transform
of the pupil mask.

00:31:57.690 --> 00:32:00.540
I wrote it in a form that
looks a bit more like a Fourier

00:32:00.540 --> 00:32:04.360
transform, and of course u and
v are now arbitrary arguments.

00:32:04.360 --> 00:32:06.360
These are the spatial
frequencies in the Fourier

00:32:06.360 --> 00:32:09.720
transform, but what
actually goes in there

00:32:09.720 --> 00:32:13.390
is these parameters over here.

00:32:13.390 --> 00:32:18.550
So basically we get again a term
that looks like a convolution.

00:32:18.550 --> 00:32:23.930
So we see that the image,
the complex optical field

00:32:23.930 --> 00:32:32.260
at the image is a convolution of
the input field times something

00:32:32.260 --> 00:32:35.555
that again we will call
the point spread function.

00:32:35.555 --> 00:32:37.180
And this point spread
function, just as

00:32:37.180 --> 00:32:41.210
in the case of the 4F system,
again here the point spread

00:32:41.210 --> 00:32:44.050
function is given as the
Fourier transform over

00:32:44.050 --> 00:32:47.830
the pupil of the
pupil mask scaled

00:32:47.830 --> 00:32:51.200
with appropriate coordinates.

00:32:51.200 --> 00:32:55.520
OK, and there is various
scaling forms and factors here.

00:32:55.520 --> 00:33:00.570
For example, this one again
ensures energy conservation,

00:33:00.570 --> 00:33:03.140
which is kind of
important, but very often

00:33:03.140 --> 00:33:06.270
in optics we don't care so much
about the absolute intensities,

00:33:06.270 --> 00:33:08.850
which means that we don't
really care about this term.

00:33:08.850 --> 00:33:11.720
What we really care about is
about the spatial distribution,

00:33:11.720 --> 00:33:15.560
like the type we're solving,
whether features make it

00:33:15.560 --> 00:33:18.830
to the image or they get
lost due to spatial filtering

00:33:18.830 --> 00:33:19.860
and so on and so forth.

00:33:19.860 --> 00:33:23.360
So very often these
multiplicative constants,

00:33:23.360 --> 00:33:25.880
we just drop them.

00:33:25.880 --> 00:33:28.560
That's sort of convention.

00:33:28.560 --> 00:33:31.520
Now, to get a little
more insight out of this,

00:33:31.520 --> 00:33:38.000
imagine for a moment that
the point spread function

00:33:38.000 --> 00:33:39.620
becomes extremely narrow.

00:33:39.620 --> 00:33:42.240
It becomes a delta function.

00:33:42.240 --> 00:33:44.330
So if you substitute
the delta function

00:33:44.330 --> 00:33:46.130
into the expression
we had before,

00:33:46.130 --> 00:33:47.780
then you get this
expression, which

00:33:47.780 --> 00:33:50.780
is of course again
very gratifying

00:33:50.780 --> 00:33:53.300
because now the output
really looks like,

00:33:53.300 --> 00:33:56.720
again, some multiplicative
term, but then it really looks

00:33:56.720 --> 00:33:59.500
like the input,
except in the input

00:33:59.500 --> 00:34:02.870
now, the coordinates
have been scaled,

00:34:02.870 --> 00:34:05.120
so therefore you can immediately
see that this term is

00:34:05.120 --> 00:34:07.210
the magnification.

00:34:07.210 --> 00:34:11.239
In fact, the lateral
magnification of the system

00:34:11.239 --> 00:34:12.960
is given by this expression.

00:34:12.960 --> 00:34:18.739
So we basically
rederived the same result

00:34:18.739 --> 00:34:21.290
that we got from
geometrical optics--

00:34:21.290 --> 00:34:24.469
namely, the lens law that
is the imaging condition,

00:34:24.469 --> 00:34:27.300
the magnification and
so on and so forth.

00:34:27.300 --> 00:34:32.480
Now we've got them back from
our wave optics approach,

00:34:32.480 --> 00:34:34.219
but we had to do
some approximations.

00:34:34.219 --> 00:34:37.280
For example, we had to
pretend that the point spread

00:34:37.280 --> 00:34:39.020
function is a delta
function in order

00:34:39.020 --> 00:34:41.688
to get the geometrical
optics result. If it's not,

00:34:41.688 --> 00:34:42.980
which is never the case, right?

00:34:42.980 --> 00:34:46.679
Delta function is a
very good approximation.

00:34:46.679 --> 00:34:50.270
So if it's not a delta
function, then the result

00:34:50.270 --> 00:34:52.940
is not exactly like this,
but it is a convolution.

00:34:52.940 --> 00:34:55.550
That is, basically this
will become blurry.

00:34:55.550 --> 00:35:00.650
Like [? Pepe ?] showed earlier,
you will get a blurred vision--

00:35:00.650 --> 00:35:04.040
or in general, an
especially filtered version

00:35:04.040 --> 00:35:06.080
of the original
input will actually

00:35:06.080 --> 00:35:08.270
survive through to the output.

00:35:13.800 --> 00:35:15.510
What I would like
to point out now,

00:35:15.510 --> 00:35:17.940
this is something that I
believe Se Baek also showed

00:35:17.940 --> 00:35:20.360
last time, the same slide.

00:35:20.360 --> 00:35:24.750
What I would like to
do is basically pay

00:35:24.750 --> 00:35:28.080
a little bit of attention
to the scaling factors here.

00:35:28.080 --> 00:35:30.450
These scaling factors are
actually very important.

00:35:30.450 --> 00:35:34.530
So I mentioned that to drop
multiplicative factors that

00:35:34.530 --> 00:35:36.150
appear in the front here.

00:35:36.150 --> 00:35:39.103
This, it is OK to drop,
but these scaling factors

00:35:39.103 --> 00:35:40.520
that go inside the
argument, these

00:35:40.520 --> 00:35:43.080
are very important
because they determine

00:35:43.080 --> 00:35:48.240
the amount of spatial filtering
that goes on inside the system.

00:35:48.240 --> 00:35:50.770
So what I will do
actually for a while

00:35:50.770 --> 00:35:54.170
is I will compare the 4F
system with a single lens

00:35:54.170 --> 00:35:55.180
similar system.

00:35:55.180 --> 00:35:57.180
So the scale factors,
again, they are different.

00:35:57.180 --> 00:36:03.470
You see f1 is inside the
transfer function, and z1

00:36:03.470 --> 00:36:05.160
in the case of the single lens.

00:36:05.160 --> 00:36:06.950
So what is the
effect of that one?

00:36:06.950 --> 00:36:10.390
Also in the incoherent case.

00:36:10.390 --> 00:36:12.730
Of course, in the
incoherent case,

00:36:12.730 --> 00:36:16.540
the transfer function
is the autocorrelation

00:36:16.540 --> 00:36:19.220
of the coherent
transfer function,

00:36:19.220 --> 00:36:23.380
and since the coherent
transfer function is basically

00:36:23.380 --> 00:36:27.430
proportional to the
pupil mask, then what

00:36:27.430 --> 00:36:31.060
we call the optical transfer
function, the incoherent case,

00:36:31.060 --> 00:36:33.520
is an autocorrelation of
the pupil mask itself.

00:36:33.520 --> 00:36:37.780
This is again a very basic
result, but again, be careful.

00:36:37.780 --> 00:36:40.390
When we compute these
autocorrelations,

00:36:40.390 --> 00:36:42.880
we have to apply
different scaling factors

00:36:42.880 --> 00:36:44.210
in the argument.

00:36:44.210 --> 00:36:44.710
OK.

00:36:44.710 --> 00:36:47.650
So I will show in a second how
this works, and I will show it

00:36:47.650 --> 00:36:49.360
in two cases.

00:36:49.360 --> 00:36:53.895
One is what we called before
the Zernike phase mask.

00:36:53.895 --> 00:36:55.520
Actually, this is
not exactly accurate.

00:36:55.520 --> 00:36:57.355
Zernike did not
invent exactly this.

00:36:57.355 --> 00:37:00.395
He invented another one
that has pi over 2 phase

00:37:00.395 --> 00:37:01.300
shift at the edges.

00:37:01.300 --> 00:37:02.290
It's like a ring.

00:37:02.290 --> 00:37:04.360
But anyway, the
function is the same,

00:37:04.360 --> 00:37:09.220
so everybody refers to all of
these types of masks as Zernike

00:37:09.220 --> 00:37:11.080
nowadays.

00:37:11.080 --> 00:37:11.980
So this is familiar.

00:37:11.980 --> 00:37:14.320
We saw a few
examples in the past

00:37:14.320 --> 00:37:19.570
when it was in the middle in the
focal plane of the 4F system,

00:37:19.570 --> 00:37:24.950
and this is the case when
we put it as a pupil mask

00:37:24.950 --> 00:37:26.510
in a single lens system.

00:37:26.510 --> 00:37:28.100
It's the same mask.

00:37:28.100 --> 00:37:30.100
It will do a very similar
thing, but there's

00:37:30.100 --> 00:37:33.110
a subtle difference, so this
is what I want to point out.

00:37:33.110 --> 00:37:35.920
So this is the
subtle difference.

00:37:35.920 --> 00:37:37.960
What you see here is, of
course, the schematics,

00:37:37.960 --> 00:37:41.320
so you see it is opaque
outside some amplitude.

00:37:41.320 --> 00:37:43.930
Then inside, you have
this little extra phase

00:37:43.930 --> 00:37:48.730
delay near the optical
access in a small region.

00:37:48.730 --> 00:37:51.430
And OK, this is the
mathematical expression

00:37:51.430 --> 00:37:53.050
that I don't want to dwell upon.

00:37:53.050 --> 00:37:55.460
I'd rather focus on
these plots here.

00:37:55.460 --> 00:38:01.450
So these two plots
are the magnitude

00:38:01.450 --> 00:38:03.550
and the phase of the mask.

00:38:03.550 --> 00:38:05.200
So the magnitude is the top.

00:38:05.200 --> 00:38:08.680
The blue plot it
goes from 0 to 1.

00:38:08.680 --> 00:38:11.800
So it is 1 within the amplitude,
so let's see if that's correct.

00:38:11.800 --> 00:38:14.380
The amplitude has a
size of 1 centimeter,

00:38:14.380 --> 00:38:19.060
so indeed this is 1
between minus 0.5 and 0.5.

00:38:19.060 --> 00:38:23.190
And the phase, well, the phase,
nobody knows what the phase is.

00:38:23.190 --> 00:38:25.450
Where the magnitude
is zero, we can not

00:38:25.450 --> 00:38:28.810
define the phase for a complex
number that equals zero.

00:38:28.810 --> 00:38:31.810
Nevertheless, let's
set it equal to zero.

00:38:31.810 --> 00:38:35.470
But what I want to emphasize
is that within the past band

00:38:35.470 --> 00:38:40.360
of the system, the phase is
0, except for a small chunk

00:38:40.360 --> 00:38:42.730
of width of 0.2
centimeters where

00:38:42.730 --> 00:38:45.230
the phase jumps to pi over 2.

00:38:45.230 --> 00:38:49.570
Pi over 2 is of course i.

00:38:49.570 --> 00:38:51.490
And this is the real
and imaginary part.

00:38:51.490 --> 00:38:53.350
These two are
actually equivalent.

00:38:53.350 --> 00:38:58.030
So the real part,
it is 1, except at

00:38:58.030 --> 00:39:02.500
the little extra phase
protrusion there where

00:39:02.500 --> 00:39:05.350
the real part goes to 0,
and the imaginary part

00:39:05.350 --> 00:39:12.010
becomes 1 because of course
when the phase equals pi over 2,

00:39:12.010 --> 00:39:15.010
then the actual complex
amplitude equals i.

00:39:15.010 --> 00:39:17.170
So that's what you see here.

00:39:17.170 --> 00:39:22.570
So these two pairs describe
both of the phase mask.

00:39:22.570 --> 00:39:26.550
So the [INAUDIBLE] transfer
functions of course

00:39:26.550 --> 00:39:28.250
are the same.

00:39:28.250 --> 00:39:31.730
I only plotted them here as
a real and imaginary part,

00:39:31.730 --> 00:39:33.570
but they have the same shape.

00:39:33.570 --> 00:39:36.330
What is really different--
and unfortunately,

00:39:36.330 --> 00:39:39.240
my plot is a little
bit too small here.

00:39:39.240 --> 00:39:40.620
You cannot see very well--

00:39:40.620 --> 00:39:43.810
is that they actually
have different sizes.

00:39:43.810 --> 00:39:47.430
This one, if you do the scaling
factors here for the numbers

00:39:47.430 --> 00:39:49.815
that I used, I think I used--

00:39:53.810 --> 00:39:56.870
so I used lambda
equals 1 micron.

00:39:59.960 --> 00:40:07.880
Lambda equals 1 micron,
f1 equals 10 centimeters,

00:40:07.880 --> 00:40:11.210
f2 equals 1 centimeter
for the 4F system.

00:40:11.210 --> 00:40:15.630
And then z1 equals
11 centimeters,

00:40:15.630 --> 00:40:23.750
z2 equals 1.1 centimeters, and
f1 equals still 10 centimeters

00:40:23.750 --> 00:40:25.060
for the single lens.

00:40:25.060 --> 00:40:27.050
And I worked those out
so that in both cases,

00:40:27.050 --> 00:40:30.570
you get the demagnification
of a factor of 10.

00:40:30.570 --> 00:40:33.100
That's why the numbers are
a little bit strange there.

00:40:33.100 --> 00:40:36.057
So in both cases, you get a
demagnification factor of 10,

00:40:36.057 --> 00:40:38.390
and I did that deliberately
because the two systems give

00:40:38.390 --> 00:40:41.060
you the same effect
kind of, but you

00:40:41.060 --> 00:40:43.940
can see in terms of geometrical
optics, they are identical.

00:40:43.940 --> 00:40:46.070
They both give you
a demagnification

00:40:46.070 --> 00:40:48.518
by a factor of 10,
but you see here

00:40:48.518 --> 00:40:50.060
that in terms of
wave optics, they're

00:40:50.060 --> 00:40:52.430
slightly different
because one of them,

00:40:52.430 --> 00:40:55.160
the 4F system is scaled
by the focal length.

00:40:55.160 --> 00:40:57.290
Its spatial frequency
extends, goes

00:40:57.290 --> 00:41:00.650
from minus 50 to 50
inverse millimeters.

00:41:00.650 --> 00:41:02.450
This is what you see here.

00:41:02.450 --> 00:41:05.960
Whereas in this case, it goes
from approximately minus 48

00:41:05.960 --> 00:41:09.020
to 48 inverse millimeters.

00:41:09.020 --> 00:41:12.610
So the single lens actually
does a slightly more severe

00:41:12.610 --> 00:41:20.428
spatial filter than the
case of the 4F system.

00:41:20.428 --> 00:41:22.720
That is to be expected, of
course, because the distance

00:41:22.720 --> 00:41:23.240
z1--

00:41:23.240 --> 00:41:25.880
you can see from here--

00:41:25.880 --> 00:41:34.520
the distance z1 that you subtend
from the object to the aperture

00:41:34.520 --> 00:41:36.710
is longer, so
therefore this system

00:41:36.710 --> 00:41:39.830
is cutting off more
angles, or more spatial

00:41:39.830 --> 00:41:43.100
frequencies than this system.

00:41:43.100 --> 00:41:44.980
We will see that in
more detail in a second.

00:41:44.980 --> 00:41:46.730
The other thing I want
to point out to you

00:41:46.730 --> 00:41:50.390
is that if you take
that autocorrelation

00:41:50.390 --> 00:41:54.380
of this function, which
is the coherent transfer

00:41:54.380 --> 00:41:58.070
function or the ATF, if you
take its autocorrelation,

00:41:58.070 --> 00:42:03.930
you obtain the OTF, which is, as
Se Baek demonstrated last time,

00:42:03.930 --> 00:42:06.230
it is the transfer
function for spatially

00:42:06.230 --> 00:42:08.060
incoherent illumination.

