00:43:11.220 --> 00:43:16.110
Let me talk a little bit more
about these scaling factors.

00:43:21.100 --> 00:43:25.580
So in this case, this is just a
clear aperture that I put here,

00:43:25.580 --> 00:43:29.980
and you can see that in the
case of the clear aperture,

00:43:29.980 --> 00:43:32.950
it's actually very easy to
do sort of the ray diagrams,

00:43:32.950 --> 00:43:34.470
and you can see also here that--

00:43:37.060 --> 00:43:38.810
well, let me back
up for a second.

00:43:38.810 --> 00:43:40.810
So you remember from
geometrical optics,

00:43:40.810 --> 00:43:43.850
we had the definition of
the numerical aperture.

00:43:43.850 --> 00:43:47.140
So we defined the numerical
aperture as the angle

00:43:47.140 --> 00:43:50.740
that we subtend towards
the optical system

00:43:50.740 --> 00:43:54.460
if we place a point
source on axis.

00:43:54.460 --> 00:43:56.570
So therefore, the
numerical aperture

00:43:56.570 --> 00:43:59.680
is limited by one of the
physical apertures that

00:43:59.680 --> 00:44:01.040
are in the system.

00:44:01.040 --> 00:44:04.450
So in the case of the 4F system,
that would be the pupil mask.

00:44:04.450 --> 00:44:06.270
At some point in
any physical system,

00:44:06.270 --> 00:44:08.920
the pupil mask
cannot be infinite.

00:44:08.920 --> 00:44:11.890
It has to be finite, so the
physical diameter of the pupil

00:44:11.890 --> 00:44:16.180
mask, assuming the lenses
themselves are large enough,

00:44:16.180 --> 00:44:19.130
the pupil mask will become
the limiting factor.

00:44:19.130 --> 00:44:22.040
And so we can compute the
numerical aperture then.

00:44:22.040 --> 00:44:27.430
It is the ratio of
the radius of the mask

00:44:27.430 --> 00:44:29.110
over the focal length, f1.

00:44:29.110 --> 00:44:33.460
You can see it very easily
from this triangle over here.

00:44:37.840 --> 00:44:39.840
And of course this is an
approximate expression.

00:44:39.840 --> 00:44:42.180
In reality, the
numerical apertures

00:44:42.180 --> 00:44:47.250
would be the sine over
the inverse tangent

00:44:47.250 --> 00:44:49.200
of this quantity,
but of course we're

00:44:49.200 --> 00:44:51.730
doing [INAUDIBLE]
approximations here,

00:44:51.730 --> 00:44:55.950
so we can drop the
trigonometric functions.

00:44:55.950 --> 00:45:01.050
In the case of the single lens
the numerical aperture is--

00:45:01.050 --> 00:45:04.290
again, you can get it from
this triangle over here,

00:45:04.290 --> 00:45:09.975
but now the one of the
orthogonal sides is z1, not f1.

00:45:09.975 --> 00:45:11.850
So you can see that the
numerical aperture is

00:45:11.850 --> 00:45:18.630
r over z1, and of course if this
system is supposed to produce

00:45:18.630 --> 00:45:22.350
a real image, as opposed
to a virtual image,

00:45:22.350 --> 00:45:25.290
then z1 must be longer than f1.

00:45:25.290 --> 00:45:29.010
You can see very clearly
from the imaging condition,

00:45:29.010 --> 00:45:32.460
1 over z1 plus 1 over
z2 equals 1 over f.

00:45:32.460 --> 00:45:35.170
If you want z2 to be positive--

00:45:35.170 --> 00:45:40.200
so for z2 to be positive, it
means I have a real image--

00:45:40.200 --> 00:45:45.060
for this, it is required
that z1 is bigger than f.

00:45:45.060 --> 00:45:48.780
So because of that, you can see
that if you have the same size

00:45:48.780 --> 00:45:51.810
pupil mask, the single lens
system would have a smaller

00:45:51.810 --> 00:45:53.400
numerical aperture.

00:45:53.400 --> 00:45:57.240
That is sort of an
unfortunate fact of life.

00:45:59.760 --> 00:46:01.650
So another thing I
want to point out here

00:46:01.650 --> 00:46:04.620
is that the numerical
aperture actually

00:46:04.620 --> 00:46:07.350
changes when you go to the
second leg of the system

00:46:07.350 --> 00:46:10.110
because, of course, the system
has angular magnification.

00:46:10.110 --> 00:46:14.130
So what started as a numerical
aperture at the input

00:46:14.130 --> 00:46:16.230
is of course an angle.

00:46:16.230 --> 00:46:18.570
If you take the
marginal ray, it is

00:46:18.570 --> 00:46:20.700
propagating at a given
angle with respect

00:46:20.700 --> 00:46:21.940
to the optical axis.

00:46:21.940 --> 00:46:25.410
By the time it comes out,
this angle will have changed.

00:46:25.410 --> 00:46:26.100
By how much?

00:46:26.100 --> 00:46:29.070
By the angular
magnification of the system.

00:46:29.070 --> 00:46:32.090
So therefore, the numerical
aperture at the output

00:46:32.090 --> 00:46:32.970
is not the same.

00:46:32.970 --> 00:46:37.800
It equals the numerical aperture
at the input times the angular

00:46:37.800 --> 00:46:39.910
magnification of the system.

00:46:39.910 --> 00:46:42.810
So this is not a
cause for confusion.

00:46:42.810 --> 00:46:44.380
We can use either one.

00:46:44.380 --> 00:46:47.490
We'll get actually the
same conclusions whether we

00:46:47.490 --> 00:46:50.010
use the numerical
aperture or the input

00:46:50.010 --> 00:46:52.470
or the numerical
aperture at the output,

00:46:52.470 --> 00:46:54.090
but we have to be a
little bit careful

00:46:54.090 --> 00:46:56.340
that we don't confuse
things, as long

00:46:56.340 --> 00:46:58.800
as we remember this
simple relationship

00:46:58.800 --> 00:47:04.120
that the two are connected
by the angular magnification.

00:47:04.120 --> 00:47:08.560
So the reason the numerical
aperture is so important is

00:47:08.560 --> 00:47:13.088
because if you consider
a circular-- of course,

00:47:13.088 --> 00:47:14.380
you cannot see the circle here.

00:47:14.380 --> 00:47:15.820
This is just the projection.

00:47:15.820 --> 00:47:20.590
But imagine that I
have a circular pupil.

00:47:20.590 --> 00:47:23.290
Then recall that the point
spread function of the system

00:47:23.290 --> 00:47:25.270
is actually the
Fourier transform

00:47:25.270 --> 00:47:29.770
of that circular pupil because
this is a clear aperture now.

00:47:29.770 --> 00:47:32.860
And we learned sometime ago--

00:47:32.860 --> 00:47:34.120
I don't remember when--

00:47:34.120 --> 00:47:36.130
but we learned that
the Fourier transform

00:47:36.130 --> 00:47:41.180
of a circular function
is this crazy [? zinc ?]

00:47:41.180 --> 00:47:45.310
so-called function that is given
by a ratio of a Bessel function

00:47:45.310 --> 00:47:48.220
to its argument, and
it's probably better

00:47:48.220 --> 00:47:50.560
to think of it as a
plot like this one that

00:47:50.560 --> 00:47:53.790
has a main lobe and then
a smaller side lobe.

00:47:53.790 --> 00:47:55.490
And actually, it
has a lot of lobes.

00:47:55.490 --> 00:48:00.340
It continues on forever, but the
size of the lobes decays away.

00:48:00.340 --> 00:48:04.810
How fast it decays away
is 1 over the argument.

00:48:04.810 --> 00:48:08.988
So what I want to point out
here is that in both cases,

00:48:08.988 --> 00:48:10.780
the point spread the
function of the system

00:48:10.780 --> 00:48:13.390
looks like this
[? zinc ?] functions.

00:48:13.390 --> 00:48:16.245
Sometimes it's also
known as an Airy disk.

00:48:16.245 --> 00:48:17.620
Not an Airy
function, by the way.

00:48:17.620 --> 00:48:20.380
Airy function is different.

00:48:20.380 --> 00:48:24.313
This one is referred
to as Airy disk.

00:48:24.313 --> 00:48:25.980
If you're curious
what Airy function, is

00:48:25.980 --> 00:48:27.930
you can open the
table of formulas.

00:48:27.930 --> 00:48:30.810
Abramowitz and [INAUDIBLE],, and
you'll see a monstrous thing.

00:48:30.810 --> 00:48:32.935
That's called the Airy
function, and this turns out

00:48:32.935 --> 00:48:35.070
to be a special case
of an Airy function.

00:48:35.070 --> 00:48:38.410
But anyway, this
is the Airy disk,

00:48:38.410 --> 00:48:42.190
and what I want to emphasize
is that in both cases,

00:48:42.190 --> 00:48:47.650
you get the same shape of Airy
disk, but different in size.

00:48:47.650 --> 00:48:51.040
And you'll get different size
because in the case of the 4F

00:48:51.040 --> 00:48:56.690
system, the size of the
aperture is the same,

00:48:56.690 --> 00:48:59.260
but because the scaling
factor is smaller--

00:48:59.260 --> 00:49:04.090
it is f1-- then you
actually get a bigger ATF.

00:49:04.090 --> 00:49:08.980
The size of the disk in the
frequency domain is bigger.

00:49:08.980 --> 00:49:11.980
Therefore, it will give you a
slightly narrower point spread

00:49:11.980 --> 00:49:13.750
function.

00:49:13.750 --> 00:49:17.260
If you work out these
ratios over here,

00:49:17.260 --> 00:49:18.760
and you work out
these coefficients,

00:49:18.760 --> 00:49:21.190
you will see that
very clearly, but I

00:49:21.190 --> 00:49:23.500
want you to get it
sort of intuitively

00:49:23.500 --> 00:49:27.910
by using the scaling theorem
of Fourier transform.

00:49:27.910 --> 00:49:31.510
In both cases, you start with
the same physical aperture,

00:49:31.510 --> 00:49:34.780
but what matters is not the
physical size of the aperture,

00:49:34.780 --> 00:49:36.490
but the numerical aperture.

00:49:36.490 --> 00:49:40.860
So in one case, you have
this numerical aperture.

00:49:40.860 --> 00:49:41.750
This is a f1.

00:49:41.750 --> 00:49:44.950
This is the physical size,
and numerical aperture

00:49:44.950 --> 00:49:47.240
is R over f1.

00:49:47.240 --> 00:49:50.570
In the other case, you have
again the same aperture,

00:49:50.570 --> 00:49:55.220
but now you have a
longer distance here.

00:49:55.220 --> 00:49:58.500
This is still R. So now
the numerical aperture

00:49:58.500 --> 00:50:01.430
would be R over z1.

00:50:01.430 --> 00:50:05.030
So the same physical
aperture in the two cases

00:50:05.030 --> 00:50:09.020
will actually give you a
different size in the ATF.

00:50:09.020 --> 00:50:10.475
This will have a bigger ATF.

00:50:16.900 --> 00:50:20.350
So the size of the ATF,
if you work it out,

00:50:20.350 --> 00:50:26.680
it will be proportional to
actually 1 over lambda f1,

00:50:26.680 --> 00:50:30.220
and the size of the ATF here--

00:50:30.220 --> 00:50:32.230
I'm exaggerating, of course--

00:50:32.230 --> 00:50:35.140
will be proportional
to 1 over lambda z1.

00:50:38.970 --> 00:50:44.080
OK, so since we've got the
smaller size of the ATF

00:50:44.080 --> 00:50:48.120
in this case, it means that
we'll get a broader PSF.

00:50:48.120 --> 00:50:50.220
So which system is better?

00:50:50.220 --> 00:50:52.630
Well, obviously this
one because this one

00:50:52.630 --> 00:50:54.610
will give you a narrower PSF.

00:50:54.610 --> 00:50:57.260
Therefore, it will give
you a smaller blur.

00:50:57.260 --> 00:50:58.510
So of course there's a caveat.

00:50:58.510 --> 00:51:01.360
I sort of took it for
granted that the desirable

00:51:01.360 --> 00:51:04.210
in an optical system is to
minimize the blur, which

00:51:04.210 --> 00:51:05.800
in most cases it's true.

00:51:05.800 --> 00:51:07.990
If for some reason someone
asked you deliberately

00:51:07.990 --> 00:51:10.750
to produce a system that
causes a lot of blur,

00:51:10.750 --> 00:51:13.600
then of course you would go for
this one, but in most cases,

00:51:13.600 --> 00:51:15.910
we try to minimize blur.

00:51:15.910 --> 00:51:19.300
So this means, given
our resources--

00:51:19.300 --> 00:51:23.410
that is, given our physical
size of the numerical aperture--

00:51:23.410 --> 00:51:27.008
we should try to maximize
the numerical aperture,

00:51:27.008 --> 00:51:28.800
and that is what the
photo system is doing.

00:51:34.702 --> 00:51:36.910
So there are a few comments
about the resolution that

00:51:36.910 --> 00:51:38.200
are in the rest of the slides.

00:51:38.200 --> 00:51:40.242
I don't want to destroy
the rest of your morning.

00:51:45.650 --> 00:51:47.930
Because the PSF
is finite, you can

00:51:47.930 --> 00:51:49.520
imagine that if
you have two point

00:51:49.520 --> 00:51:51.213
sources that are at distance.

00:51:51.213 --> 00:51:52.630
So now this is
like an experiment.

00:51:52.630 --> 00:51:54.950
I'm moving two point
sources together.

00:51:54.950 --> 00:51:57.410
There will come a point
where the two point

00:51:57.410 --> 00:51:59.120
sources will merge.

00:51:59.120 --> 00:52:01.730
And if this is
your image now, you

00:52:01.730 --> 00:52:05.067
don't really know whether you
had one point source or two.

00:52:05.067 --> 00:52:06.650
Now, of course you
say, well, you also

00:52:06.650 --> 00:52:08.030
get twice the intensity.

00:52:08.030 --> 00:52:10.520
That's true, but very
often you don't know

00:52:10.520 --> 00:52:11.940
the intensity you started with.

00:52:11.940 --> 00:52:14.180
For example, if you're
looking at the sky,

00:52:14.180 --> 00:52:15.680
and you're looking
at the bright dot

00:52:15.680 --> 00:52:18.770
and you're trying to decide,
is it one star or two stars?

00:52:18.770 --> 00:52:22.160
Well, so far we cannot yet
go to the stars and measure

00:52:22.160 --> 00:52:24.020
their brightness, right?

00:52:24.020 --> 00:52:25.700
We can only measure
the total brightness

00:52:25.700 --> 00:52:27.192
that we receive here.

00:52:27.192 --> 00:52:29.150
So therefore, if you're
looking at a telescope,

00:52:29.150 --> 00:52:31.850
and you see this, you
don't know if there's

00:52:31.850 --> 00:52:36.380
one star or two stars that
are too close to be resolved

00:52:36.380 --> 00:52:38.480
by your telescope.

00:52:38.480 --> 00:52:41.000
So actually, this
sort of situation

00:52:41.000 --> 00:52:47.550
was dealt with by a fellow
called Rayleigh, and of course,

00:52:47.550 --> 00:52:49.280
the size of the
PSF, as I worked out

00:52:49.280 --> 00:52:51.960
before, it depends on
the numerical aperture.

00:52:51.960 --> 00:52:54.950
So I will go over
this in more detail

00:52:54.950 --> 00:52:56.990
later, but this
is just a preview

00:52:56.990 --> 00:53:00.605
that the numerical aperture
actually gives you an idea--

00:53:00.605 --> 00:53:02.480
I actually believe also
Professor [INAUDIBLE]

00:53:02.480 --> 00:53:04.520
mentioned it in one
of the past lectures.

00:53:04.520 --> 00:53:07.040
The numerical aperture
gives you an idea

00:53:07.040 --> 00:53:12.980
about the capability of your
system to resolve point images.

00:53:12.980 --> 00:53:15.890
So imagine that each
one of these lobes

00:53:15.890 --> 00:53:19.190
here corresponds to the point
spread function of one point

00:53:19.190 --> 00:53:20.360
object.

00:53:20.360 --> 00:53:23.300
So in this case, they were
resolved because I spaced them

00:53:23.300 --> 00:53:28.580
so that the diameter
of the main lobe

00:53:28.580 --> 00:53:32.570
falls exactly on one
null of the other lobe.

00:53:32.570 --> 00:53:34.700
So if you work it out,
and you take into care

00:53:34.700 --> 00:53:38.000
into where the zeros
of the Bessel function

00:53:38.000 --> 00:53:39.830
are located and
so on, you come up

00:53:39.830 --> 00:53:41.880
with an expression
that looks like this.

00:53:41.880 --> 00:53:43.760
The space in between
the two sources

00:53:43.760 --> 00:53:47.210
is 1.22 times the
wavelength divided

00:53:47.210 --> 00:53:49.130
by the numerical aperture.

00:53:49.130 --> 00:53:53.510
And of course this would
be at the input plane.

00:53:53.510 --> 00:53:57.980
So this would be the spacing
at the input required

00:53:57.980 --> 00:54:00.740
so that the two sources
can be resolved.

00:54:00.740 --> 00:54:04.400
But when you look at the
output, the distance of course

00:54:04.400 --> 00:54:06.980
would be given by a
similar expression,

00:54:06.980 --> 00:54:09.680
but the numerical
aperture at the output

00:54:09.680 --> 00:54:11.330
would appear in this case.

00:54:11.330 --> 00:54:14.720
And of course this is sort of
the most common definition.

00:54:14.720 --> 00:54:17.120
Some books define
the resolution--

00:54:17.120 --> 00:54:19.430
instead of the diameter,
they use the radius,

00:54:19.430 --> 00:54:22.550
so they come up with an
expression that is exactly 1/2.

00:54:22.550 --> 00:54:23.960
Which one is
correct, it actually

00:54:23.960 --> 00:54:25.190
depends on your requirements.

00:54:25.190 --> 00:54:28.700
If you require a
very crisp image,

00:54:28.700 --> 00:54:33.195
or if you're dealing with
a very noisy situation,

00:54:33.195 --> 00:54:34.820
then you go for this
one because as you

00:54:34.820 --> 00:54:37.380
can imagine if you organize
noise into this one,

00:54:37.380 --> 00:54:38.870
then it becomes
progressively more

00:54:38.870 --> 00:54:41.480
difficult to resolve
the two spots.

00:54:41.480 --> 00:54:43.190
So in a very noisy
environment, when

00:54:43.190 --> 00:54:44.840
you have a very
little light, then

00:54:44.840 --> 00:54:46.088
you go for this definition.

00:54:46.088 --> 00:54:47.630
If you have plenty
of light, then you

00:54:47.630 --> 00:54:50.690
can possibly resolve two sources
that are very close like this,

00:54:50.690 --> 00:54:51.190
right.

00:54:51.190 --> 00:54:53.210
Here you see you have
very poor contrast.

00:54:53.210 --> 00:54:54.800
You basically have to rely--

00:54:54.800 --> 00:54:56.300
in order to resolve
the two sources,

00:54:56.300 --> 00:54:59.610
you have to rely on this
little dip in density.

00:54:59.610 --> 00:55:02.120
So if your signal is
noisy, this may be lost,

00:55:02.120 --> 00:55:04.277
and then you cannot
resolve anymore.

00:55:04.277 --> 00:55:05.860
OK, so that's a
preview of resolution.

00:55:05.860 --> 00:55:08.400
We'll talk about this
a little bit more.